iracollege.lk Official website]\n*[http://zahiracollege.tumblr.com/post/36500470924/zahira-college-anthem The College Anthem]\n\n[[Category:1892 establishments in Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1892]]\n[[Category:Schools in Colombo]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Western Province\u2192Western Province, Sri Lanka,Minister\u2192Minister (government)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zahira_College,_Colombo"}
{"title_page": "Alag\u00f6z, Mardin", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Beth Kustan\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \n|settlement_type        = \n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Turkey\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Turkey\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{TUR}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Turkey|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Mardin Province]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Turkey|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Midyat]]\n|subdivision_type3      = \n|subdivision_name3      =\n|subdivision_type4      = \n|subdivision_name4      =\n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|population_as_of               =2019\n|population_footnotes           =<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nufusune.com/158071-mardin-midyat-bethkustan-mahallesi-nufusu|title=BETHKUSTAN MAHALLES\u0130 N\u00dcFUSU M\u0130DYAT MARD\u0130N|author=<!--Not stated--> |access-date=25 April 2020|website=T\u00fcrkiye N\u00fcfusu}}</ref>\n|population_total               =167\n|population_density_km2         =\n|timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|coordinates            = {{coord|37.495|N|41.626|E}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Beth Kustan''' ({{lang-syr|\u0712\u071d\u072c \u0729\u0723\u071d\u0722\u0710}},<ref name=\"Syriaca\">''[http://syriaca.org/place/537.html Beth Qustan]''. The Syriac Gazeteer.</ref>{{refn|Alternatively transliterated as Beth Qustan,<ref name=\"Syriaca\" /> Boqusyono,<ref name=\"Gaunt2012\" /> or Bekusyone.<ref>''[http://www.syriacchristianity.info/bio/SyriacOrthodox/bio_TimotheosAktas.htm Mor Timotheos Samuel Aktas]''. Malankara Syriac Christian Resources.</ref>|group=nb}} {{lang-tr|Alag\u00f6z}}) is a village in [[Mardin Province]] in southeastern [[Turkey]]. It is located in the district of [[Midyat]] and the historical region of [[Tur Abdin]].\n\nIn the village, there is a church of [[Elijah|Mor Eliyo]].<ref name=\"Takahashi\" />\n\n==Etymology==\nThe Syriac name of the village is derived from \"beth\" (\"house\" in Syriac) and \"Kustan\" (\"Constantine\" in Syriac), thus Beth Kustan translates to \"house of Constantine\".<ref name=\"Takahashi\" >Takahashi (2011), p. 163</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Church of Mor Eliyo was constructed in 343 AD.<ref>{{cite news |title=Assyrians return to Turkey from Europe to save their culture|url=https://www.trtworld.com/magazine/assyrians-return-to-turkey-from-europe-to-save-their-culture-10131|accessdate=11 January 2020|date=5 September 2017|first=Murat |last= Sofuoglu|work=[[TRT World]]}}</ref> It is suggested that the village was founded by a member of the Roman [[limitanei]] (frontier militia) named Constans in the 4th century AD.<ref>Palmer (1990), p. 55</ref>\n\nIn 1900, Beth Kustan was inhabited by an estimated 200 [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] families.<ref name=\"Oez\">{{cite web |url=https://elar.soas.ac.uk/Collection/MPI1035085|title=Documentation of the Beth Qustan Dialect of the Central Neo-Aramaic language, Turoyo|last=Oez|first=Mikael|date=2017|publisher=SOAS, Endangered Languages Archive, ELAR|access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref> At the onset of the [[Assyrian genocide]], in 1915, Haco, ''[[Agha (title)|agha]]'' (chief) of the Kurtak clan, warned the villagers of an impending attack by Turkish and Kurdish soldiers.<ref name=\"Gaunt2006\">Gaunt (2006), p. 223</ref> Despite initial hesitation, upon receiving news of the massacre of Assyrians at [[\u0130zb\u0131rak, Midyat|Zaz]], all but two villagers fled to [[An\u0131tl\u0131, Midyat|Hah]].<ref name=\"Gaunt2006\" /> Beth Kustan was subsequently ransacked by Kurdish soldiers, and the two remaining villagers were killed.<ref name=\"Gaunt2006\" /> The villagers resisted Kurdish and Turkish attacks at Hah until a truce was negotiated by Haco, but were not able to leave until \u00c7elebi, ''agha'' of the Heverkan clan, helped them to return to Beth Kustan in 1922<ref name=\"Gaunt2012\">Gaunt (2012), p. 264</ref><ref name=\"Gaunt2006\" />\n\nThe village was officially named Alag\u00f6z in the 1930s as a result of the state's [[Geographical name changes in Turkey|turkification policy]].<ref name=\"Oez\" /><ref name=\"Bianet\" /> In the 1960s,<ref name=\"Bianet\" /> most of the village's population emigrated abroad to the [[Netherlands]], [[Germany]], and [[Switzerland]].<ref name=\"Courtois\" /> In 1993, it was alleged that seven villagers were detained and tortured by [[Village guard system|Turkish paramilitaries]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6aa7d18.html|title=U.S. Department of State Country Report on Human Rights Practices 1993 - Turkey|author=<!--Not stated--> |access-date=11 January 2020|publisher=United States Department of State|date=30 January 1994}}</ref> As of 2013, 15-23 Assyrian families inhabit Beth Kustan.<ref name=\"Courtois\">Courtois (2013), p. 149</ref> On 12 February 2015, Beth Kustan was restored as the official name of the village.<ref name=\"Bianet\">{{cite news |title=Assyrian Village Name Returned For 1st Time in Turkey|url=http://bianet.org/english/minorities/162227-assyrian-village-name-returned-for-1st-time-in-turkey|accessdate=11 January 2020|date=12 February 2015|first=Nilay |last= Vardar|work=[[Bianet]]}}</ref> The inhabitants speak [[Turoyo language|Turoyo]], a dialect of Neo-Aramaic.<ref name=\"Oez\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n*Saint [[Gabriel of Beth Qustan]] (573/574-648), Syriac Orthodox Bishop of Tur Abdin\n*Timotheos Samuel Akta\u015f (b. 1945), Syriac Orthodox Archbishop of Tur Abdin\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal|first1=S\u00e9bastien de|last1=Courtois|title=Tur Abdin : R\u00e9flexions sur l\u2019\u00e9tat pr\u00e9sent descommunaut\u00e9s syriaques du Sud-Est de la Turquie,m\u00e9moire, exils, retours|journal=Cahier du Gremmamo, vol. 21|date=2013|language=fr||url=https://www.academia.edu/7228305/Tur_Abdin_R%C3%A9flexions_sur_l%C3%A9tat_pr%C3%A9sent_des_communaut%C3%A9s_syriaques_du_sud-est_de_la_Turquie_m%C3%A9moires_exils_et_retours_Cahier_du_GREMAMO_n_21_2013_p._113-150|pages=113-150}}\n*{{cite book | last1 =Gaunt|first1 =Gaunt|date=2006|title=Massacres, Resistance, Protectors: Muslim-Christian Relations in Eastern Anatolia During World War I|publisher=Gorgias Press}}\n*{{cite book | last1 =Gaunt|first1 =Gaunt|date=2012|chapter=Relations between Kurds and Syriacs and Assyrians in Late Ottoman Diyarbekir|title=Social Relations in Ottoman Diyarbekir, 1870-1915, ed. Joost Jongerden, Jelle Verheij|publisher=Brill|pages=241-267}}\n*{{cite book | last1 =Palmer|first1 =Andrew|date=1990|title=Monk and Mason on the Tigris Frontier: The Early History of Tur Abdin|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}\n*{{cite book | last1 =Takahashi|first1 =Hidemi|date=2011|chapter=Also via Istanbul to New Haven- Mss. Yale Syriac 7-12|title=Islamic Philosophy, Science, Culture, and Religion: Studies in Honour of Dimitri Gutas, ed. Felicitas Opwis, David Reisman|publisher=Brill|pages=157-179}}\n\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Tur Abdin]]\n[[Category:Villages in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Mardin Province]]\n[[Category:Places of the Assyrian genocide]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Alag\u00f6z\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \n|settlement_type        = \n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Turkey\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Turkey\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{TUR}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Turkey|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Mardin Province]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Turkey|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Midyat]]\n|subdivision_type3      = \n|subdivision_name3      =\n|subdivision_type4      = \n|subdivision_name4      =\n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|population_as_of               =2019\n|population_footnotes           =<ref name=\"Nufusu\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nufusune.com/157493-mardin-derik-alagoz-mahallesi-nufusu|title=ALAG\u00d6Z MAHALLES\u0130 N\u00dcFUSU DER\u0130K MARD\u0130N|author=<!--Not stated--> |access-date=25 April 2020|website=T\u00fcrkiye N\u00fcfusu}}</ref>\n|population_total               =90\n|population_density_km2         =\n|timezone=[[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|coordinates            = {{coord|37.495|N|41.626|E}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Alag\u00f6z''' ({{lang-syr|\u0712\u071d\u072c \u0729\u0723\u071d\u0722\u0710|Beth Kustan}})<ref name=\"Syriaca\">''[http://syriaca.org/place/537.html Beth Qustan]''. The Syriac Gazeteer.</ref>{{refn|Alternatively transliterated as Beth Qustan,<ref name=\"Syriaca\" /> Boqusyono,<ref name=\"Gaunt2012\" /> or Bekusyone.<ref>''[http://www.syriacchristianity.info/bio/SyriacOrthodox/bio_TimotheosAktas.htm Mor Timotheos Samuel Aktas]''. Malankara Syriac Christian Resources.</ref>|group=nb}} is a village in [[Mardin Province]] in southeastern [[Turkey]]. It is located in the district of [[Midyat]] and the historical region of [[Tur Abdin]].\n\nIn the village, there is a church of [[Elijah|Mor Eliyo]].<ref name=\"Takahashi\" />\n\n==Etymology==\nThe Syriac name of the village is derived from \"beth\" (\"house\" in Syriac) and \"Kustan\" (\"Constantine\" in Syriac), thus Beth Kustan translates to \"house of Constantine\".<ref name=\"Takahashi\" >Takahashi (2011), p. 163</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Church of Mor Eliyo was constructed in 343 AD.<ref>{{cite news |title=Assyrians return to Turkey from Europe to save their culture|url=https://www.trtworld.com/magazine/assyrians-return-to-turkey-from-europe-to-save-their-culture-10131|accessdate=11 January 2020|date=5 September 2017|first=Murat |last= Sofuoglu|work=[[TRT World]]}}</ref> It is suggested that the village was founded by a member of the Roman [[limitanei]] (frontier militia) named Constans in the 4th century AD.<ref>Palmer (1990), p. 55</ref>\n\nIn 1900, Beth Kustan was inhabited by an estimated 200 [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] families.<ref name=\"Oez\">{{cite web |url=https://elar.soas.ac.uk/Collection/MPI1035085|title=Documentation of the Beth Qustan Dialect of the Central Neo-Aramaic language, Turoyo|last=Oez|first=Mikael|date=2017|publisher=SOAS, Endangered Languages Archive, ELAR|access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref> At the onset of the [[Assyrian genocide]], in 1915, Haco, ''[[Agha (title)|agha]]'' (chief) of the Kurtak clan, warned the villagers of an impending attack by Turkish and Kurdish soldiers.<ref name=\"Gaunt2006\">Gaunt (2006), p. 223</ref> Despite initial hesitation, upon receiving news of the massacre of Assyrians at [[\u0130zb\u0131rak, Midyat|Zaz]], all but two villagers fled to [[An\u0131tl\u0131, Midyat|Hah]].<ref name=\"Gaunt2006\" /> Beth Kustan was subsequently ransacked by Kurdish soldiers, and the two remaining villagers were killed.<ref name=\"Gaunt2006\" /> The villagers resisted Kurdish and Turkish attacks at Hah until a truce was negotiated by Haco, but were not able to return to Beth Kustan until 1922 with the aid of \u00c7elebi, ''agha'' of the Heverkan clan.<ref name=\"Gaunt2012\">Gaunt (2012), p. 264</ref><ref name=\"Gaunt2006\" />\n\nThe village was officially named Alag\u00f6z in the 1930s as a result of the state's [[Geographical name changes in Turkey|turkification policy]].<ref name=\"Oez\" /><ref name=\"Bianet\" /> In the 1960s,<ref name=\"Bianet\" /> most of the village's population emigrated abroad to the [[Netherlands]], [[Germany]], and [[Switzerland]].<ref name=\"Courtois\" /> In 1993, it was alleged that seven villagers were detained and tortured by [[Village guard system|Turkish paramilitaries]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6aa7d18.html|title=U.S. Department of State Country Report on Human Rights Practices 1993 - Turkey|author=<!--Not stated--> |access-date=11 January 2020|publisher=United States Department of State|date=30 January 1994}}</ref> As of 2013, 15-23 Assyrian families inhabit Beth Kustan.<ref name=\"Courtois\">Courtois (2013), p. 149</ref> On 12 February 2015, it was announced that Beth Kustan was to be restored as the official name of the village,<ref name=\"Bianet\">{{cite news |title=Assyrian Village Name Returned For 1st Time in Turkey|url=http://bianet.org/english/minorities/162227-assyrian-village-name-returned-for-1st-time-in-turkey|accessdate=11 January 2020|date=12 February 2015|first=Nilay |last= Vardar|work=[[Bianet]]}}</ref> however, as of 31 March 2019, it has not yet been implemented.<ref name=\"Nufusu\" /> The inhabitants speak [[Turoyo language|Turoyo]], a dialect of Neo-Aramaic.<ref name=\"Oez\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n*Saint [[Gabriel of Beth Qustan]] (573/574-648), Syriac Orthodox Bishop of Tur Abdin\n*Timotheos Samuel Akta\u015f (b. 1945), Syriac Orthodox Archbishop of Tur Abdin\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal|first1=S\u00e9bastien de|last1=Courtois|title=Tur Abdin : R\u00e9flexions sur l\u2019\u00e9tat pr\u00e9sent descommunaut\u00e9s syriaques du Sud-Est de la Turquie,m\u00e9moire, exils, retours|journal=Cahier du Gremmamo, vol. 21|date=2013|language=fr||url=https://www.academia.edu/7228305/Tur_Abdin_R%C3%A9flexions_sur_l%C3%A9tat_pr%C3%A9sent_des_communaut%C3%A9s_syriaques_du_sud-est_de_la_Turquie_m%C3%A9moires_exils_et_retours_Cahier_du_GREMAMO_n_21_2013_p._113-150|pages=113-150}}\n*{{cite book | last1 =Gaunt|first1 =Gaunt|date=2006|title=Massacres, Resistance, Protectors: Muslim-Christian Relations in Eastern Anatolia During World War I|publisher=Gorgias Press}}\n*{{cite book | last1 =Gaunt|first1 =Gaunt|date=2012|chapter=Relations between Kurds and Syriacs and Assyrians in Late Ottoman Diyarbekir|title=Social Relations in Ottoman Diyarbekir, 1870-1915, ed. Joost Jongerden, Jelle Verheij|publisher=Brill|pages=241-267}}\n*{{cite book | last1 =Palmer|first1 =Andrew|date=1990|title=Monk and Mason on the Tigris Frontier: The Early History of Tur Abdin|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}\n*{{cite book | last1 =Takahashi|first1 =Hidemi|date=2011|chapter=Also via Istanbul to New Haven- Mss. Yale Syriac 7-12|title=Islamic Philosophy, Science, Culture, and Religion: Studies in Honour of Dimitri Gutas, ed. Felicitas Opwis, David Reisman|publisher=Brill|pages=157-179}}\n\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Tur Abdin]]\n[[Category:Villages in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Mardin Province]]\n[[Category:Places of the Assyrian genocide]]\n", "name_user": "Mugsalot", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected mistake", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alag%C3%B6z,_Mardin"}
